honestior auriqa] This was the reverse of the Greek usage, where the ἡνίοχυς was of inferior rank to the παραβάτης, and often styled θεράπων. These chariots were driven by the warrior, and carried a number of his fighting men of lower rank. On reaching the enemy's line, these last leaped down and fought on foot. The ‘aurigae' drove off to a little distance and stood aloof. In case the ‘clientes' were distressed, they were carried off in the chariots. Cf. Caesar, iv. 33.
